    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Friday Morning</p>
      <p>My Sweet Mate. This letter I think will be a surprise to you &amp; the Hen. I intend it as much for her as for you.-- You will find me I expect, improved very much since Wednesday. Yesterday I went out in the chair about 12 o'clock, which you will be pleased to hear, &amp; that I was rather the better than the worse.</p>
      <p>I seem to be gaining more decidedly the last two days than I have done yet, and as this is a really beautiful morning, I think I shall if the afternoon is propitious &amp; my habit comes in time, take my first ride, about which I am not the least nervous.--</p>
      <p>I send you a book in which I have marked a passage I want the Hen &amp; you &amp; the public (that is Lady O &amp; Miss M) to consider attentively, &amp; to say whether it appears</p>
      <p>possible that anything now come to light can grossly contradict such evidence.-- Hester is going to copy &amp; send it to the Fellowes's.-- Bring the book back with you, &amp; please not to forget it, as it is wanted here.--</p>
      <p>From the violent abuse Hester heard even from the very liberal Mr Fellowes, about Unitarians, I feel sure they have no idea of our apostacy, otherwise common civility to her must have at least moderated them.-- I am rather sorry to hear of Locke's</p>
      <p>great orthodoxy, &amp; that he now thinks it scarcely right to name the devil, except in an under tone &amp; concealed terms, such as the Evil Spirit. Mrs Locke &amp; your Mother can only allude to him with the most distant deference &amp; delicate reserve.--</p>
      <p>You must really try &amp; hereticise your brother a little bit. He has better sense, &amp; ought to use it.--</p>
      <p>I am struck with the similarity I find in some of Channing's ideas, with Babbage's. If Babbage were morally a Channing, which to preserve anything like a just proportion between his intellect &amp; the Christian</p>
      <p>responsible part of our nature, he should be, what a blazing &amp; glorious light he would shine forth!--</p>
      <p>Tell the Hen I am vexed at her thinking I can only take a mathematical astronomical view of the Heavens, &amp; that if I were to write verses on the Moon, the subject would be the living things of our Satellite, and that I should wonder whether its surface so fair &amp; so bright as viewed from this earth, would open as perplexing a perspective of mixed</p>
      <p>mixed weal &amp; woe as own orb does, when more nearly approached ^^, &amp; whether the shadows which are dimly visible in her glittering countenance, are truly emblematical of the spiritual state suited to her physical conditions.-- Then I should go on to the aspect our planet presents to the spirits of the Moon, &amp;c &amp;c &amp;c, &amp; in short I could compose a very sublime poem; but not a word therein of mathematics &amp; the laws of motion.--</p>
      <p>So the Hen has not quite such a booky of a daughter</p>
      <p>as she supposes.--</p>
      <p>I do believe I shall turn out poet at last, if I live to be 50, and a much wiser thing is a poet of 50 than a poet of 15!--</p>
      <p>A great deal more than I have sketched out, could I say about the Moon, and tell the Hen I half think it is the growth of my Ideality &amp; Causality that has made me ill, &amp; that the excitement of writing all this has swelled one side of my face &amp; made me feel quite painfully animated. Within the last 4 months</p>
      <p>there is a perceptible alteration in the shape of my forehead, which I know by passing my fingers across it.--</p>
      <p>A pert Avis</p>
      <p>[The letter is written in pencil but at the bottom of this page are a few ink calculations in an unknown hand, not transcribed.]</p>
